---
// AgenticAIExplainer — CONTENT-02. 250-400 word body + 2-column contrast element.
// Direct response to the buggerd post-mortem (visitors didn't realize what it was).
---
<section id="agentic-ai" class="border-b border-muted/20">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-20 md:py-24">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-muted">What's the difference</p>
    <h2 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl mt-4 text-fg">
      An assistant helps when you ask. An employee owns the function.
    </h2>
    <div class="mt-8 space-y-5 text-fg/90 leading-relaxed">
      <p>AI assistants are good at the task in front of them. You describe a problem, they help you work through it. That's genuinely useful. But it's still you doing the job — just faster. An AI employee is something different: it owns a function on an ongoing basis, works it without being prompted, and surfaces the things that need a human instead of the things that don't.</p>
      <p>The failure mode most AI products gloss over is reliability at the function level. A demo that writes a good email is not the same as a system that handles your inbox every morning. Unsupervised AI tends to hallucinate steps, make confident mistakes, and fail silently. A reliable AI employee needs explicit checkpoints — places in its loop where it verifies its own work before it acts, and asks a question instead of guessing when it hits the boundary of its remit.</p>
      <p data-educator-end>That's what JigSpec builds. Every product is a named function with a defined scope, tool access, and a review gate before anything leaves your environment. The employee analogy isn't marketing — it's the design constraint. Clear remit. Audit log. Kill switch. You always know what it did and why.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-10 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 border border-muted/30 rounded-md p-6">
      <div>
        <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-muted">An assistant</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-fg">Helps when you ask. Waits between sessions. Has no ongoing responsibility and no way to act on your tools without you in the loop for each step.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest text-accent">An employee</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-fg">Owns the function. Works the queue while you sleep. Surfaces the two things that needed a human and handles the thirty-eight that didn't — with a log you can read on Friday.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script>
  import { track } from '../../lib/analytics';

  const sentinel = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-educator-end]');
  if (sentinel) {
    let fired = false;
    const obs = new IntersectionObserver(
      (entries) => {
        for (const e of entries) {
          if (e.isIntersecting && !fired) {
            fired = true;
            track('educator:scroll_complete', {});
            obs.disconnect();
          }
        }
      },
      { threshold: 1.0 }
    );
    obs.observe(sentinel);
  }
</script>
